<br>
Is EQ addictive?  Hell yeah it is.  The game, the building of a character, the feeling of teamwork and accomplishment, the &quot;quick fix&quot; of accomplishment that comes from killing something with 60 other people.   Yeah...it's addictive.  The people who deny that are the people who generally have a problem.  We all know the game is addictive.<br>
<br>
I'm 30 years old.  I've been playing games like D&amp;D, RPGs, FFGFs and MMORGs since I was 12 years old.  That's 18 years, and in all that time, every single game I've been played has been called addictive and dangerous.<br>
<br>
They are right, all fantasy games are addictive....fantasy is addictive in itself.  Are they dangerous?  Well....I'm a member of the NRA as well...and we have a slogon....Guns don't kill people...people kill people.   Does EQ have something to do with this kids suicide?  I'd bet money on it.  Should this kid have been playing EQ?  Well, the first lines on CBS said &quot;Struggling with a learning disability and emotional problems.&quot;  My guess...no...he shouldn't have delved in fantasy.<br>
<br>
Fantasy is wonderful.  It allows us to escape reality and pretend (at least for awhile) to be something that were not...or even to let us explore persona's that we can't display in real life.  But, just like anything, it can be dangerous when taken to the extreme...even then, only if the person who is playing it can't handle the extremes.  Ben Stein let his 13 year old kid play?  WTF?  I mean the guys supposed to be a brain, did he not have enough common fucking sense to be a parent?  <br>
<br>
Yes, EQ is addictive and yes, in the wrong hands (just like drugs, guns, cars, and sex) it can be very dangerous.  But one thing people need to start realizing is that people make their own desicions, and if they are not capable of doing so, then the consequences will often end up being less than appealing. <p>                 
